article.headline: Lady Vols win 50th straight home game
article.linkText: Tennessee tunes up Vandy, faces Duke next
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- With solid defense and good rebounding,
No. 2 Tennessee was unstoppable at home.

Shyra Ely scored 22 points for Tennessee, which beat Vanderbilt
79-54 Thursday night in a tuneup for Saturday's showdown at
top-ranked Duke.

Brittany Jackson added 15 points to help the Lady Vols (15-1,
5-0 Southeastern Conference) win their 50th straight home game in
league play.

Improved rebounding has been a priority for Tennessee coach Pat
Summitt.

She said being third in the SEC by outrebounding opponents an
average of 6.7 a game is not good enough.

"Last year we won rebounding in the country at plus 15. I'm
really challenging this team," Summitt said. "This is one game
they responded."

Tennessee outrebounded the Commodores (14-3, 2-2) by 13, and
Vanderbilt lost its fifth straight game against the Lady Vols and
dropped to 0-19 in Knoxville.

They didn't help themselves much by turning over the ball a
season-high 26 times.

"I'll give them the credit. I'd like to say none of them were
forced," Vanderbilt coach Melanie Balcomb said. "We're a young
team with young guards, and this was the first time they had seen
this kind of pressure."

Each team had 11 steals, but Tennessee thrived in transition.

Trailing 44-30 with 13:46 left, Vanderbilt had an 8-0 run over
the span of one minute, and Abi Ramsey capped it with a steal and
three-point play that trimmed the lead to 44-38.

But the Lady Vols responded with a 12-0 spurt that included
baskets off three steals and led 56-38 with 9:42 to go after
Jackson's pull-up jumper.

"I think we were beat in every area of the game," Balcomb
said. "To get within six, I'm surprised."

That's when Tennessee turned up the defense.

"Defense is our philosophy at Tennessee. That's what Pat likes,
and we want to make her happy," Tennessee's Ashley Robinson said.

The Commodores got as close as 11 points twice thereafter, the
last on Dee Davis' layup with 6:10 remaining. But Ely quickly
scored on the other end to keep Vanderbilt at bay.

Jackson's only miss was a free throw. She was 5-of-5 from the
field -- including 2-of-2 from beyond the arc.

Ramsey led Vanderbilt with 13 points and Carla Thomas had 10.

Vanderbilt had 15 turnovers by halftime and has had at least 20
turnovers in eight games this season.

Jenni Benningfield, one of Vanderbilt's best players, put in 18
minutes, the most over the last four games since sustaining a
stress fracture in her right foot. She finished with seven points.

Tennessee got off to a quick start, leading 22-8 midway through
the first half.

Vanderbilt cut the lead to seven twice after trailing by 14 but
couldn't maintain a rally. The Commodores' Ashley Earley had a
layup to make it 24-17 but missed a free throw on the play.

The Lady Vols followed with a basket by Ely and a three-point
play by Robinson to restore the lead to 12 with 4:11 left in the
first half.
